read all the .md files. do all coding that's related to AG-Grid in accordance with search_docs in the AG-Grid MCP server (Angular 35.1.0 is the latest version it exposes, use that for AG Grid docs lookups).	We will only be working on my aesthetic branch (albert-2sandbox), never touching any other branch aside from develop, and never merging to main
ensure that you add unit test cases for the functions/code you create, to make sure future changes do not break the functionality.

Read design_handoff_rfq_polish/SPEC_V2.md in full before writing a single line of code. Then read src/app/helpers/ag-grid/grid-themes.config.ts, src/app/pages/rfq/rfq.component.scss, src/app/helpers/ag-grid/rfq-grid/rfq.grid.config.ts, and src/app/helpers/ag-grid/rfq-detail-grid/rfq.detail.grid.config.ts. Then stop and tell me your implementation plan before touching anything.

`HARD CONSTRAINTS — violating any of these is a bug, not a style choice:`

`1. NO --ag-* CSS variables. NO .ag-theme-alpine overrides. NO .ag-row-selected { background } rules. This grid uses AG Grid v35's Theming API (themeQuartz.withParams). Every color and typography change goes into the withParams({}) object in grid-themes.config.ts. If you write a CSS variable or an ag-theme-alpine rule, delete it.`

`2. For structural CSS that isn't a theme param (heights, seam shadow, cell-class tints, row group colors) use ::ng-deep in rfq.component.scss on real AG Grid classes (.ag-header-row, .ag-cell-last-left-pinned, .ag-full-width-row, etc.). This is the correct mechanism. The spec §5 tags every element with its mechanism — follow those tags exactly.`

`3. DO NOT set pinned: 'left' in colDefs and call it done. Saved Views override colDef defaults silently. To set frozen identity columns, do both: (a) update the Default GridLayout record so new users get it, AND (b) call gridApi.applyColumnState() on firstDataRendered for price_code, pic, and desc only. See spec §5d for the exact call.`

`4. DO NOT call sizeColumnsToFit() on the detail sub-grid if any column has flex: 1. They conflict. The note column gets flex: 1; remove any existing sizeColumnsToFit() call from detail-cell-renderer.component.ts.`

`5. The detail sub-grid's live column IDs are price, name, note — NOT quote_price, vendor_note. Use the live IDs.`

`6. DO NOT rewrite or replace any calculation logic, edit behavior, fill-handle behavior, undo stack, or getMasterFiledName() calls. Appearance only.`

`Implement in this sequence — one commit per step, show me the diff before committing each:`

`Step 1 (lowest risk): themeQuartz.withParams() update in grid-themes.config.ts + all ::ng-deep CSS in rfq.component.scss (grid chrome, header heights, group-band tints, seam, row group rows, scenario cell tints, re-quote cell color, button radius/color, toolbar dividers). This is pure styling — zero logic changes.`

`Step 2: Density toggle — new segmented control in rfq.component.html, setDensity() method in rfq.component.ts using setGridOption('rowHeight') + resetRowHeights(), persisted to localStorage. See spec §5i for exact markup and TypeScript.`

`Step 3: Status pill cell renderer + Step indicator cell renderer. See spec §5f and §5g for exact markup, styles, and color mappings. Register each as a cellRenderer in rfq.grid.config.ts.`

`Step 4: Detail sub-grid polish — column reorder (Name · Price · Lead · CBM · Price Terms · FOB Country · FOB Port · Note), flex on note column, remove sizeColumnsToFit(), apply detail renderer SCSS from spec §5k.`

`Step 5 (most complex, do last): Collapsible scenario column groups — migrate the 24 flat scenario columns to 8 ColGroupDef objects with columnGroupShow. Test with admin role (sees all 24 cols) and sales role (sees only Price for Sales). Verify column group state saves and restores via the existing onSaveLayout. See spec §1 from the original README.md for the buildScenarioGroups() pattern.`

`After each step: run the existing specs (rfq.component.spec.ts, rfq.grid.config.spec.ts, rfq.detail.grid.config.spec.ts). Add a test for any new behavior. Show me the result before moving to the next step.`

`The visual target is design_handoff_rfq_polish/RFQ Prototype.html — open it in a browser to see exactly what it should look like.`


The detail sub-grid loads columns from the backend (getGridHeader 'rfq_detail'), so editing rfq.detail.grid.config.ts won't change the live grid.
The right model for backend-driven column defs

The backend owns column identity and order. The frontend can apply rendering overrides on top of whatever the backend returns. These are two separate concerns:



What	Owner	Mechanism

Column order, colIds, visibility	Backend (getGridHeader 'rfq_detail')	Backend change

flex, minWidth, type, cellClass	Frontend post-processing	Override map in detail-cell-renderer

sizeColumnsToFit() removal	Frontend	Delete the call

Visual styling (card, chips, action bar)	Frontend	component SCSS

Revised Step 4 — replace the original with this

Step 4: Detail sub-grid — flex sizing, visual polish.



The sub-grid columns come from the backend (getGridHeader 'rfq_detail'), so

rfq.detail.grid.config.ts does NOT control the live grid. Do not rely on it.



4a. BACKEND — column order (one backend change only):

In the endpoint that serves getGridHeader 'rfq_detail', reorder the returned

columns to: name · price · lead_time · cbm_pc · price_terms · fob_country ·

fob_port · note. This is a sort of the returned array, nothing else. Confirm

the live colIds with the backend team before doing this — do not guess at names.



4b. FRONTEND — colDef overrides after backend load:

In detail-cell-renderer.component.ts, find where the backend column response

is processed before being set on the detail grid. Add an override step there:



  const DETAIL_OVERRIDES: Record<string, Partial<ColDef>> = {

    'name':  { minWidth: 180, pinned: 'left' },

    'price': { minWidth: 100, type: 'rightAligned' },

    'note':  { flex: 1, minWidth: 200 },

  };



  const cols = backendCols.map(col => ({

    ...col,

    ...(DETAIL_OVERRIDES[col.colId] ?? {})

  }));



Apply this merged cols array to the detail grid. Do NOT hardcode a full column

list — only the overrides map. All other columns keep whatever the backend says.



4c. FRONTEND — remove sizeColumnsToFit():

Find and delete any sizeColumnsToFit() call in detail-cell-renderer.component.ts.

The flex: 1 on the note column fills remaining space — calling sizeColumnsToFit()

on top of it will fight and win unpredictably.



4d. FRONTEND — detail renderer SCSS only (no colDef changes):

Apply the card container, header, chip, and action-bar styles from

SPEC_V2.md §5k to detail-cell-renderer.component.scss. These are pure CSS —

they do not depend on column IDs or order.

One thing to confirm before 4a: what are the live colIds, actually. The spec guesses price, name, note, lead_time etc. — but if the real response uses different names, 4b's override map needs to match. The SCSS in 4d works regardless.


The RFQ grid isn't wired to the Theming API (it's on legacy ag-theme-alpine), so spec §4's withParams edits won't render
The ::ng-deep rules in SPEC_V2 §5 are all still correct — they target real AG Grid classes and work on Alpine. The only thing that breaks is §4's withParams() block. Replace that one block with CSS variables on the Alpine wrapper. Everything else in the spec stays the same.



Replacement for SPEC_V2 §4 (Step 1 only)

Instead of editing grid-themes.config.ts, add this block to rfq.component.scss:



// rfq.component.scss — Alpine CSS variable overrides

// Replaces the themeQuartz.withParams() block from SPEC_V2 §4.

// All ::ng-deep rules in §5 stay exactly as written.



::ng-deep .ag-theme-alpine {

  // ── Accent ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  --ag-alpine-active-color:             #D81B60;

  --ag-range-selection-background-color: rgba(216, 27, 96, 0.07);

  --ag-range-selection-border-color:    #D81B60;

  --ag-checkbox-checked-color:          #D81B60;



  // ── Backgrounds ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  --ag-background-color:                #ffffff;

  --ag-odd-row-background-color:        #fbfcfd;

  --ag-row-hover-color:                 #fff5f8;

  --ag-selected-row-background-color:   #fff5f8;

  --ag-header-background-color:         #f7f9fc;



  // ── Text ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  --ag-foreground-color:                #475569;

  --ag-header-foreground-color:         #475569;

  --ag-secondary-foreground-color:      #7b8a9a;



  // ── Borders ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  --ag-border-color:                    #e7e9ee;

  --ag-secondary-border-color:          #eef1f5;

  --ag-row-border-color:                #eef1f5;

  --ag-border-radius:                   8px;



  // ── Typography ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  --ag-font-size:                       13px;

  --ag-font-family:

    "Hanken Grotesk", -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, "Segoe UI", system-ui, sans-serif;

}

Exact replacement text for the Claude Code Step 1 prompt

Replace the "Step 1" block in your Claude Code prompt with this:



Step 1 (lowest risk): Visual reskin via Alpine CSS variables + ::ng-deep CSS.



The RFQ grid is on legacy ag-theme-alpine, NOT the Theming API. Do NOT touch

grid-themes.config.ts. Do NOT write themeQuartz.withParams(). Instead:



1a. In rfq.component.scss, add a ::ng-deep .ag-theme-alpine { } block and set

the CSS variables listed in SPEC_V2.md §4 "Replacement block." These variables

are the correct mechanism for the Alpine theme — they set background, row hover,

selection, header, accent, borders, font family, and font size.



1b. All ::ng-deep rules in SPEC_V2.md §5 (header heights, group-band tints, seam

shadow, row group rows, scenario cell tints, re-quote cell, button styles, status

bar) are correct as written. Apply them to rfq.component.scss exactly as the spec

says — the mechanism tags ([::ng-deep CSS], [colDef cellClass], etc.) are all valid

for the Alpine theme.



1c. headerFontWeight, headerFontSize, cellHorizontalPadding, and text-transform

uppercase on header text have no Alpine CSS variable equivalents — handle them

with ::ng-deep CSS rules (already specified in SPEC_V2 §5a).



This is pure CSS — zero logic or API changes. Show me the diff before committing.

Two things to tell Claude Code if it gets confused

If it tries to write --ag-header-font-weight — that's not a real Alpine variable; stop it and use ::ng-deep .ag-header-cell-text { font-weight: 600 } instead.

If it writes --ag-* variables outside .ag-theme-alpine — they won't scope correctly; the block must be ::ng-deep .ag-theme-alpine { }.

The detail-grid reorder and frozen-identity default are DB-data changes (not repo code)
Both can be handled entirely in code — no DB changes needed. Here's the practical call on each.
Detail sub-grid column order → frontend post-processing, skip the DB
The Step 4b override map already solves flex/minWidth in code. Extend it to also enforce order:

```typescript
// detail-cell-renderer.component.ts — after backend cols arrive

const DESIRED_ORDER = ['name', 'price', 'lead_time', 'cbm_pc',
                       'price_terms', 'fob_country', 'fob_port', 'note'];

const OVERRIDES: Record<string, Partial<ColDef>> = {
  name:  { minWidth: 180, pinned: 'left' },
  price: { minWidth: 100, type: 'rightAligned' },
  note:  { flex: 1, minWidth: 200 },
};

const cols = [...backendCols]
  .sort((a, b) => {
    const ai = DESIRED_ORDER.indexOf(a.colId);
    const bi = DESIRED_ORDER.indexOf(b.colId);
    return (ai === -1 ? 999 : ai) - (bi === -1 ? 999 : bi);
  })
  .map(col => ({ ...col, ...(OVERRIDES[col.colId] ?? {}) }));

```

Unknown colIds (anything not in `DESIRED_ORDER`) sort to the end. No DB touch, no backend coordination. Tell Claude Code: "the detail sub-grid column reorder is handled entirely in the frontend override step — skip the backend DB change."
Frozen identity → `applyColumnState` in code, skip the DB
The DB path ("update Default GridLayout record") is the tidy long-term fix, but it requires backend/admin access and coordination. The code-only path achieves the same result immediately and is already in the spec (§5d):

```typescript
// rfq.component.ts — in onFirstDataRendered or onGridReady (after view is restored)
this.gridApi.applyColumnState({
  state: [
    { colId: 'price_code', pinned: 'left' },
    { colId: 'pic',        pinned: 'left' },
    { colId: 'desc',       pinned: 'left' },
  ],
  // applyOrder: false — don't reorder columns, just set pinned state
});

```

This runs after the saved View is applied, so it wins over whatever the View says. It's idempotent — safe to run on every load. Existing saved Views are not modified; they just get the three identity columns re-pinned on top.
The trade-off: if a user deliberately unpins Description (say, to save horizontal space), this will re-pin it on every reload. If that's a concern, add a localStorage flag:

```typescript
const userOverridePinned = localStorage.getItem('rfq:unpin-identity');
if (!userOverridePinned) {
  this.gridApi.applyColumnState({ state: [...], });
}

```

Tell Claude Code: "skip the Default GridLayout DB change entirely. Use `applyColumnState` on `firstDataRendered` as specified in SPEC_V2 §5d. The DB change is deferred."
Updated Step 4 + Step 3 note for Claude Code
Add these two lines to your prompt:

```
For step 4a (detail column reorder): handle it entirely in the frontend
override step using the sort pattern above — no backend or DB change needed.

For frozen identity (step 3): skip the Default GridLayout DB update.
Use applyColumnState on firstDataRendered only. Defer the DB change.
```

