### Theme Modes


[Theme Modes](ag-mcp://article/theming-colors) allow you to define multiple colour schemes within a single theme, that can be toggled dynamically using a `theme-mode` HTML attribute.


To use Theme Modes, you first need to create light and dark colour schemes by chaining another `withParams` method onto the `themeQuartz` object, passing an additional string parameter to name the scheme:


```
const myTheme = themeQuartz
    .withPart(iconSetMaterial)
    .withParams(
        {
            // Existing theme params...
        },
        'light' // Light scheme name
    )
    .withParams(
        {
            backgroundColor: '#1e1e2f',
            foregroundColor: '#e2e8f0',
            headerBackgroundColor: '#2d2d44',
            selectedRowBackgroundColor: 'rgba(110, 168, 254, 0.2)',
            spacing: 10,
            fontSize: 12,
        },
        'dark' // Dark scheme name
    );

@Component({
    selector: 'app-root',
    template: `<ag-grid-angular [theme]="theme" />`,
})
export class AppComponent {
    theme = myTheme;
}
```


The active colour scheme can then be controlled by setting the `data-ag-theme-mode="mode"` attribute on any parent element of the grid, commonly the `html` or `body` elements:


```
@Component({
    selector: 'app-root',
    template: `
        <button (click)="toggleThemeMode()">{{ buttonText }}</button>
        <ag-grid-angular [theme]="theme" />
    `,
})
export class AppComponent implements OnInit {
    theme = myTheme;
    isDarkMode = false;
    buttonText = 'Enable Dark Mode';

    ngOnInit() {
        document.body.dataset['agThemeMode'] = 'light';
    }

    toggleThemeMode() {
        this.isDarkMode = !this.isDarkMode;
        const nextMode = this.isDarkMode ? 'dark' : 'light';
        document.body.dataset['agThemeMode'] = nextMode;
        this.buttonText = this.isDarkMode ? 'Enable Light Mode' : 'Enable Dark Mode';
    }
}
```


